Introduction

The Nixxis Supervisor gives you the means to reach and keep optimal Customer Interaction through an easy to use interface. The Nixxis Supervisor provides you with all the tools you need to achieve this.

-      Easy to configure so that it enables you to see exactly what you need.

-      Tools to help you coach your agents and improve Customer Interaction

-      Views on all the important aspects of the Nixxis Contact Suite:

o    Agent view.

o    Team view.

o    Inbound and outbound view.

o    Queue view.

This document will outline the different insights you need to work with the Nixxis Supervisor. Furthermore we will explain how to configure and use the tools provided by the Nixxis Supervisor. In the next part we describe all the views and what data they provide. At the end of the document, in the appendix, there is more information about principles that the Nixxis Contact Suite uses in relationship with the Nixxis supervisor.

So let’s get started!

 

Get started with the supervisor

Overview

This chapter describes how to get access to the Nixxis Supervisor and how to use the navigator screen.

Starting the Nixxis Supervisor

The Nixxis Supervisor is a web application and therefore needs a browser to run in. Browsers that can be used are Internet Explorer, Firefox, Safari or Opera. Start the browser of your choose and go to the address bar and type the URL of your supervisor.

Example:

After entering the correct URL you will see the next screen where you can enter the logon information.

The supervisor must now provide logon information to be able to start using the application (see: Nixxis Administration guide for more information about creating supervisor agents).

Then provide the following login information:

-      User account: the unique identifier provided by the administrator to logon to the system.

-      Password: password of the agent who wants to logon.

-      Domain: for future use.

When this is done you are ready to logon to the system by clicking the  button. There is also the option to click on the  button to reset all the fields to their default values. Once the logon information is correct you will be directed to the Nixxis Supervisor navigator window.

Navigator window

On a successful logon this window will appear: 

This window has two main areas. The first is the ‘Navigator toolbar’ and the second is the ‘Dashboard’.

The ‘dashboard’ area provides the supervisor with a quick overview of what is going on in general on the system.

The ‘navigator toolbar’ gives the supervisor access to the windows with the detail view on the Nixxis Contact Suite (NCS).

Dashboard area

We will first look into the dashboard in greater detail. As already mentioned this area gives you a general overview of the NCS (Nixxis Contact Suite). This area is split into 4 sections ‘queue, ‘inbound’, ‘outbound’ and ‘agent’.

Navigator toolbar

The goal of the ‘navigator toolbar’ is to enable the supervisor to easily navigate to any of the detailed views on the Nixxis Contact Suite.


This is what the ‘navigator toolbar’ looks like:

By simply clicking on one of the icons the detailed views are accessible. (See chapter ‘working with the nixxis supervisor views’ for more information about the different views.).

 The following options are available to the supervisor:

Working with the Nixxis Supervisor views

Overview

The next chapter will explain how the Nixxis Supervision views are working and how to configure them.

Detailed information and detail on the different columns that can be used can be found in the following chapter ‘description of the columns.’

Layout of a view window

The basic layout of all views look like:

On this layout we can see 3 main areas:

  1. Toolbar: area shows the toolbars with all the options the supervisor can use in the specific view.
  2. Main view: is the area where the list of the view that was selected is displayed.
  3. Information panel: shows extra information on a selected column in the main view.

Toolbar area

Overview

In the toolbar area the supervisor has access to the different options of a view. There are 3 types of toolbars a supervisor can use:

-       Navigator toolbar.

-       Configuration toolbar.

-       Coaching toolbar.

Depending on the selected view, toolbars and options that can be used for that view are made available to the supervisor. For example the ‘coaching toolbar’ is only available on the agent view because that is the area where an agent can be selected.

Navigator toolbar

Overview

This is the same toolbar as the ‘Navigator toolbar’ on page 11. The current view will not be shown in the toolbar. For example if the agent view is the active view then this will not be visible in the navigator toolbar.

Configuration toolbar

Overview

The configuration toolbar is used to customise the view, which allows the supervisor to select the parameters he/she is interested in.

The next options are at the disposal of the supervisor:

-          A label to indicate that this is the option toolbar of the view. It is not clickable. The icon will be different for each of the views:

o        Agent view.

o        Inbound view.

o        Outbound view.

o        Queue view.

o        Teams view.

-          Show or hide the ‘Information panel’ (see page 14 for more information).

-          Column selection (see page 14 for more information).

-          Select the group by field (see page 15 for more information).

-          Create user defined columns (see page 16 for more information).

Show or hide the ‘Information panel’

This option toggles the visibility of the ‘Information panel’. By default, the information panel is visible to the supervisor.

Information panel visible.

Information panel invisible.

Column selection

When the option ‘Column selection’  is clicked, a new window will appear that gives the supervisor the ability to select the columns he wants to see.

On the right, there is an example of a ‘Column selection’ window. When the window is opened for the first time it presents the current status of the columns in the ‘main view’.

In the window we see 3 columns:

-      Name of the column.

-      Selection box:

o     The column isn’t visible in the main view.

o     The column is visible in the main view.

-      Column category.

When the supervisor wants to see a column, he simply has to click on the selection box and be sure that it is checked ‘’. If he doesn’t want to see the column he has to uncheck ‘’ the selection box. The ‘’ button will update the main view. He can also click on the ‘’ button to apply the change and close the ‘Column selection’ window.

The ‘’ button will reset the change made by the supervisor and the current selection will be restored. When the supervisor clicks on the ‘’ button no change will be made to the column selection and the window will close. The window can also be closed by clicking the ‘’ button in the upper right corner of the window. But this will not apply the change you made to the column select and will not reset the selection you made in the column selection window. So the next time you open the window, you will have your selection as you made it (not presenting the selection in the main view) previously.

When all the columns cannot be displayed in the column selection window, the supervisor can either resize the window or us the scrollbar that will be visible on the right side of the column selection window.

In the last column you can see the ‘Column category’. Each of the columns provided by the Nixxis Contact Suite has been put into a category. The Nixxis Supervisor knows the following categories:

-      Parameters.

-      Real-time.

-      History.

-      System columns.

-      Custom columns (or User defined columns). See section ‘User defined columns’ on page 16 for more information about the ‘user defined columns.

More information about the ‘categories’ can be found on page 26.

Details about the different columns of the different views can be found in the following chapter ‘description of the columns’ on page 26.

Group by window

By clicking the ‘’ select grouping button, the following window will appear:

In this window the supervisor can select which grouping he wants to see and on which column the grouping must be done in the main view.

A grouping is used to bound information together that belongs together. For example we can group all agents who work on the helpdesk. This makes it easier to compare results of items that belong together.

In the administrator (see ‘Nixxis Administrator General Principles’ manual for more information about the administrator) we can link a group to an agent. This group is the default group field in the Nixxis supervisor. But in the supervisor you can do the grouping on any column available in that view.

Select in the dropdown list the column on which the grouping has to happen. If there is no grouping required, select the first option ‘-None-’ from the list. When the selection is made click, on the ‘’ button to apply the change to the main view. Click on the ‘’ button or  button in the upper right corner of the window to close the window.

Rows that do not have a value for the selected column or where the value is nil, will get the default group item, with the description ‘Default’.

The ‘group list’ is a table that shows all the know group descriptions. It also tells if the group is expanded or collapsed.

A group item in the list looks like this:

Each group item has a description and can be collapsed or expanded. In front of  the description of a group item, there is an icon that shows if the group is collapsed or expanded. The icon ‘’ tells you that the group is collapsed and when you click on this icon, the group will be expand and the icon will change to ‘’. When this icon is clicked the group will collapse again.

Grouping in the main view looks like this:

When there are no items to display under a group item, that group item will not be displayed in the main view.

There are two ways of grouping:

-      Grouping on columns with ‘id values’: some columns, like the ‘teamid’ column of the agent view, are lists of ids. In that case the grouping for those columns is configured to use the description value in the corresponding list (in our example the description of the team list). This also means that the row in the list will be displayed in all its group items where we have an id on. So if the agent has a member of two teams, he will be displayed under those two group items.

-      Grouping on columns with ‘values’: the value of the column is the group item. If there is no value, then it will get the default group item.

To know how a column will be grouped, go to chapter ‘description of the columns’ on page 26.

User defined columns

The window to create ‘User defined columns’ can be access by clicking on the ‘’ button.

The ‘User defined columns’-window is used to create columns defined by the supervisor. This gives the supervisor a powerful tool to customise the Nixxis supervisor and monitor his Nixxis Contact Suite.

A user-defined column is a column where the supervisor can choose the information that is shown. This information can consist in a calculation of existing columns. It can be numeric, text values or a combination of the two.

When the window is open, we can see 3 different parts in the window. The first part is where a selection can be made. Click on the ‘’ button to add a new column. Use the dropdown list to select an existing column. And then click on the ‘’ button to edit the selection or on the ‘’ button to remove the column.

The second part is where the new column can be configured or the existing one can be edited.

-      Name: the name of the column is also the name that is displayed in the column header.

-      Description: the description of the column.

-      Style: how the cell will be display. Options that can be selected are text, numeric, percent and time. More information can be found in the section ‘Parameters of a column’ on page 21.

-      Visible: is this new column default visible in the main view. For more information on the main view go to section ‘Main area’ on page 19.

-      Visible in panel: is this column visible in the ‘information panel’ when the panel type is ‘Details panel’. See for more information in the section ‘Detail panel’ on page 23.

In the big ‘text area’ under the configuration, the supervisor can enter the value of the new column. This value can be static, dynamic or a combination of the two. The supervisor also has the option to use functions that are available in the JavaScript language (For more information about this, go to the section ‘The JavaScript language’ on page 42).

The Nixxis Supervisor provides a function called ‘this. ([Js name])’ to give access to the existing columns (see the individual chapters on the view to have more information about the ‘Js names’ that you can use).

Example: this.GetValueOf(Agent.Parameters.Firstname());
This returns to the first name of the agent(More information about this function on page 44).

The ‘’ button can be used to test the value of your user defined column. For retrieving data from a row, the evaluation is using the currently selected item in the main view(see ‘Main area’.on page 19 to select an item). It will also display an error description if there is a problem. The result of the evaluation will be displayed in the textbox next to the ‘’ button. The value displayed in the textbox is the value without the style applied to it. This means for example, that if the style is set on ‘Time’, the result will not be ’00:00:30’ but will be ‘30000’. This enables to check the accurate value of the formula.

The third and last part of the window is the button bar. The ‘’ button will save the current values and close the window. When clicking on the ‘’ button, the window will close without saving and the ‘’ button can be used to save the current column configuration without exiting the window.

Coaching toolbar

Overview

The ‘Coaching toolbar’ contains tools to help monitoring the agents in the Nixxis Contact Suite. This to help the supervisor achieve an optimal customer interaction.

The flowing options are available:

-          A label to indicate this is the coaching toolbar. It is not clickable.

-          To use the ‘listen’ function (see ‘Listen’ on page ‘19’).

-          The ‘intrude’ function (see ‘Intrude’ on page ‘19’).

-      or    Start or stop recording a conversation (see ‘Recording’ on page ‘19’).

Listen

The listen function can be used by the supervisor to listen into a conversation of the agent.

To do this the supervisor has to first select an agent from the list and press the ‘’ button to activate the listing. If he wants to stop the listening, the supervisor has to click on this button again.

Intrude

The intrude function allows the supervisor to intrude into a conversation of the agent. This means that a supervisor can participate in a conversation between the agent and the customer. When the supervisor is using the intrusion, all the parties will be able to talk and hear each other.

If the supervisor wants to use this function, he has to select an agent from the list and click on the ‘’ button to activate it, click again to stop it.

Recording

The recording function allows the supervisor to record the conversation of an agent.

To use the function the supervisor has to first select an agent from the list and then click on the ‘’ button. When the recording is active the button will have this ‘’ icon. To stop the recording the supervisor has to click on this button again.

Main area

Overview

The main area is used to display a list of the requested data. For example, if the ‘agent view’ is selected, it will display a list of all the active agents. If the ‘inbound view’ is selected, it will display a list of all the inbound activities, etc. .

Here is an example of such a list:

Row

We can see different types of rows in the main area.


First of all we have the header. This is used to indicate what the column name is.

The second one is the group row indicator. We only have this row when grouping is active. Here we can see the name of the group and if the group is collapsed (indicated by ‘’) or expanded (indicated by ‘’). More information about how to use and configure groups can be found in section ‘Group by window’ on page 15.

The most important row is the item row. This one shows the data as we configure it (see ‘Configuration toolbar’ on page ‘13’). When the mouse goes over one of these items, the item will be highlighted. Just click one time to select the item. When it is selected, it will look like this:

After having selected an item, the data in the information panel will update too (see page ‘22’.for more information about the information panel).

Columns

Overview

Each row has a set of columns that contains the information about that item. The purpose of this chapter is to describe which types of columns there are and what kind of parameters there are, in order to have a better understanding of what the information in those columns means.

The individual column descriptions of the different views can be found in the chapter ‘description of the columns’ on page 26.

Parameters of a column

A column has the following main parameters:

1.    Name.

2.    Description.

3.    Type.

4.    Style.

5.    Visible.

6.    Visible in information panel (see section ‘Information panel area’).

7.    Information panel type (see section ‘Information panel area’).

The ‘name’ of the column is used in the header to briefly describe the meaning of the column. Next to the name, we have the ‘description’ of the column that gives a more detailed description of the column and can be seen in the information panel.

Each column has a parameter ‘type’. This parameter indicates the different possible ‘values’ we can have in a column (graph, value, list of ids …). In addition to these types, we can put a formatting which is defined in the parameter ‘style’.

The first type is the ‘value type’. This is a value that is provided by the Nixxis Contact Suite, e.g. the ‘number of waiting calls’. This value cannot be changed by the supervisor, but it can be used by the supervisor in the ‘User defined columns’. The second we have is the ‘graphic type’. This contains no data but uses columns of the first type. A column of this type looks like this ‘’. Each element within the graphical bar is represented in a different colour. To know what the colour means, you can click on the column and it will be shown in the ‘Information panel area’. The next type we have is the ‘list type’. This type is a list of elements represented by their ids. For example, an agent can be a member of multiple teams, so the ‘Agent.Parameters.TeamId’ represents the ids of these teams. When the supervisor clicks on a column of this type, more information is shown in the ‘Information panel area’ together with some extra information about the ids. When this column is displayed in the main view the supervisor will not see the list of the ids but instead the amount of element in the list will be displayed. The last type is ‘compute type’. This type is used for the ‘User defined columns’. So this type does not contain any real data but computes its value from a predefined formula.

The columns of type ‘value’ and ‘compute’ have an extra parameter that is called ‘style’. There are four styles:

-      Text: alignment is on the left, no other special formatting.

-      Numeric: alignment is on the right, no other special formatting. If the value is not a numeric value or a ‘nil’ then it is set to 0.

-      Time: alignment is set to the right. The value is formatted to ‘H:MM:SS’. The input value is a numeric value that expresses the time in milliseconds, if this value is not numeric, then it will be set to 0. For example: ‘3665000’ will become ’1:01:05’.

-      Percent: alignment is set to the right. The value is formatted to ‘0.00%’, if the input value is not numeric, then it will be set to 0.

The parameter ‘visible’ tells if the column will be visible in the main view by default or not. The parameter ‘visible in information panel’ tells whether the column needs to be visible in the information panel or type ‘Detail panel’ (more information on page 23).

The last parameter is ‘information panel type’ to tell what kind of information to show in the information panel. See next chapter for more information.

Information panel area

Overview

The information panel is used for displaying extra information about the current selected column. Depending on the configuration of the column (see section ‘Columns’ on page 21) there will be a specific information display.

There are three different parts in the information panel area. At the top, you will find  the name of the column that was last selected and below it, we see the description of that column. The third and last part displays the information area with the panel. The following are the 4 types of panels:

  1. Detail panel: shows a vertical view of the columns. Is also the default panel.
  2. Graphical bar panel: shows information about a selected graphic type.
  3. Column history panel: shows historical peak values for a selected column.
  4. Information on column list type: shows information about the ids in a column of the list type.

The next chapters will explain these in more detail.

Detail panel

The ‘detail panel’ shows a vertical view of all the columns of the selected row and includes the ones that have been set to invisible with the ‘column selection’ option.

On this panel there are two columns, the first one tells you the descriptions of the column and the second shows you the current value for the column.

Graphical bar panel

The ‘graphical bar panel’ provides the supervisor with information about the column of the graphic type. In a table, you will find all the colours and the value they represent.

The first column shows the colour and the column next to it shows the current value. The last column gives us the name of that column.

Column history panel

The next panel is the ‘column history panel’. This panel gives the supervisor a short history list of the peak values over a time interval for the selected column. The peak value is the largest value that there was during a time interval. The graph is a graphical view of the list of peak values against the complete list. This means that the highest value is 100% of the total length of the graph and will be put in red. The other values are put against it.

Example:

We will illustrate this with the following example of waiting calls in inbound. The time interval is 30 seconds and the list length is 12.

This table shows for each 10 seconds what the peak value is. In red we can see the peak value of the interval, in this case 30 seconds. We also put the values in a graph as we can see here:

In the next part we will show in detail what happens when the intervals of 30 seconds are triggered.

The first interval

When the first interval is past the following will be shown in the ‘column history panel’:

In this interval (-30), the peak value was 6. Because 6 is the highest number, there is only 1 interval for now; the total length of the graph is completely red. And for the other items in the list, the graph is empty.

Second interval

When the next interval is past, it will look like this:

-      Interval 1 (-60) the peak value was 6.

-      Interval 2 (-30) the peak value was 5.

So the highest value is still 6 and this graph will be fully red. The value 5 is 83,33% of the highest value and this bar will be filled up to 83,33%.

Third interval

When the next 30 seconds have gone by, the situation will be as follows:

-      Interval 1 (-90) the peak value was 6.

-      Interval 2 (-60) the peak value was 5.

-      Interval 3 (-30) the peak value was 9.

The highest value is now 9 so this will be 100% red and the other graphs will be change to match.

And so forward.

The number of values in the list can be set by the system administrator as can also be done with the time interval. In this example the length of the list is set to 12 and the time interval is 30 seconds.

Information on column list type

The last panel is the ‘information on column list type’. This panel is used for the columns that are defined as ‘list type’. Let’s take the example of the column ‘Team.Parameter.Queues’. This column represents the list of queue ids that are linked with that team. In this panel you have the description of these ids.

 

Description of the columns

Overview

In this chapter we will talk about the description and default settings of the columns (see page 21 for more information about the parameters of column).

Categories

The Nixxis Supervision splits the columns in different categories. The next categories are known by the Nixxis Supervisor:

-      Parameters: contains mainly columns about the configuration or description of an item. Example: name, description, dialling mode …

-      Real time: our columns about the current status of the item.

-      History: gives an overview of what happened during a time period.

-      System columns: Other columns used by the Nixxis Supervisor.

-      Custom columns: or ‘user defined columns'. Columns created by the supervisor. See chapter ‘User defined columns’ on page 16 for more information.

Appendix

Outbound dialling modes

There are 7 different dialling modes that can be defined for outbound activities:

-      CallbacksOnly: no new records are dialled; only records that were dialled previously and were closed by indicating that the record needed to be called back at a certain time are dialled.

-      Preview: the agents are first prompted with the record that will be dialled.

-      Progressive: after terminating a call, the next call for that agent is dialled. The agent is prompted with the record details when the communication has been established.

-      Power: the system calls out on more than 1 line per agent that becomes available. This assures that the time between 2 calls is limited.

-      Restricted Power: same as power dialling but less aggressive.

-      Predictive: the system “predicts” when it needs to start dialling and how many lines it needs, to keep the time between 2 conversations as low as possible.

-      Unattended: the system calls all numbers and plays the IVR defined in the pre-processor field in the general section. Depending on that IVR, a call can be routed to an agent or not. This method is typically used for notification and confirmation activities.

Agent status and agent actions

Introductory remarks

In this part of the documentation, the concept of ‘Agent Status’ will be clarified through different illustrations and examples, to make the used lexicon in this documentation easier to understand.

The above flowchart describes the daily work cycle of a call centre agent using a call centre application. In short, these are the steps that a call centre agent follows:

-      The agent logs into the call centre application by entering his username and/or password.

-      After the agent logs in, he is automatically in pause.

-      The agent clicks on ready and waits to receive a call.

-      The agent is connected to a customer and talks to him.

-      When the conversation is finished and the customer is disconnected, the agent takes a moment to do the necessary ‘After call’ work. This means that the agent completes the history of the customer and updates the customer record.

-      After finishing the script the agent has 3 options:

o    He can take another call by clicking again on ready

o    He can go into pause

o    He can stop working by logging off.

Agent Status

The agent status used in the Nixxis software is based on the above example. The definition for agent status is ‘the global situation of an agent at a certain time’.

The agent statuses used in the software are:

-      Waiting: The agent is waiting to be connected to a contact.

-      Online: The agent is online with one or more contacts.

-      Wrap-up: The agent is not connected to a contact anymore and is doing the ‘After call’ actions (updating customer record & history)

-      Pause: The agent is logged onto the system but is not working on any contact and not waiting to receive calls from the system.

Log in and log out are not considered as agent statuses, but as events. Because of this they don’t have a duration.

In order to have a better view on the agent status, take a look at the illustration below, which shows a part of the daily work cycle of a call centre agent.

1.    Agent logs in

2.    The agent status is automatically set to Pause

3.    Agent clicks on ready

4.    The agent status is set to waiting. The agent is now awaiting a call from the system

5.    The agent status is set to Online as soon as the agent is connected with a customer

6.    The customer disconnects from the agent

7.    The agent status is now set to wrap-up after the customer disconnected.

8.    After wrap-up the agent can wait for another call, go into pause or log off.

Agent Actions

As mentioned earlier, the agent statuses represent “the global situation” of an agent. The agent status is derived from the individual contact(s) of the agent.

In the system, each contact is divided into so-called “agent actions”. These actions specify a certain condition of the contact during the whole online contact process.

The agent actions defined in the software are:

-      Dialling: This action indicates that the system is trying to connect a contact to the agent.

-      Online: This action indicates that the agent is online with a contact.

-      On hold: This action indicates that the contact is set on hold. During this time the contact is not connected to the agent anymore.

-      Wrap-up: This action indicates that the agent is disconnected with the contact and that the agent is completing the after call actions of that contact.

The Nixxis software allows the agent to handle multiple contacts at the same time.

To make this easier to understand, the following examples will illustrate different situations with one or more contacts and the link between agent status and agent actions.

Example 1: one voice contact.

This illustration shows one contact (top arrow) with the appropriate agent actions, against the global agent status (middle arrow), during a fictive time period (bottom arrow).

T1:     Agent logs into the system and is set automatically into pause. (This can vary depending on agent settings). When the agent clicks on ready, the agent status will change into waiting.

T2:     The agent is in waiting status. This means that the agent waits to be connected to a contact.

T3:     When a contact is initiated (Call A in this example) to be connected to an agent, it receives the action ‘Agent Dialling’. This action describes the sequence during which a contact is trying to connect to an agent. In the meantime the general status of the agent is still ‘waiting’.

T4:     When the contact is connected to the agent, the ‘agent dialling’ sequence (agent action) ends and the ‘online’ sequence begins. This means that the agent is connected to the contact and is talking to the contact.  Since there is no other contact, the agent status is the same as the agent action, meaning ‘online’.

T5:     When the agent puts the contact temporary on hold, the current ‘online’ sequence is ended and a new one, ‘on hold’ is started.  Because the contact is still connected to the agent, the global status remains ‘online’.

T6:     When the agent retrieves the contact, the ‘on hold’ sequence ends and a new ‘online’ sequence starts. Again, since there are no other contacts, the agent status remains ‘online’.

T7:     Once the contact is disconnected, it initiates the ‘wrap-up’ sequence.  This sequence (agent action) gives the opportunity to the agent to complete the call with additional information.  Since there are no other contacts, the global status of the agent also changes into ‘wrap-up’.

Example 2: two voice contacts.

This illustration is the same as example 1, except that in this example the agent takes a second call.

This illustration shows two contacts (top arrows) with the appropriate agent actions, against the global agent statuses (middle arrow), during a fictive time period (bottom arrow).

T1:     Agent logs into the system and is set automatically into pause (this can vary depending on agent settings). When the agent clicks on ready, the agent status will change into waiting.

T2:     The agent is in waiting status. This means that the agent waits to be connected to a contact.

T3:     When a contact is initiated (Call A in this example) to be connected to an agent, it receives the action ‘agent dialling’. This action describes the sequence during which a contact is trying to connect to an agent. In the meantime the general status of the agent is still ‘waiting’.

T4:     When the contact is connected to the agent, the ‘agent dialling’ sequence (agent action) ends and the ‘online’ sequence begins. This means that that the agent is connected to the contact and is talking to the contact. Since there is no other contact, the agent status is the same as the agent action, meaning ‘online’.

T5:     A second contact is initiated (Call B). This has no influence on the current call or the current general status.

T6:     Call A is put on hold by the agent and call B is being connected to the agent. The agent responds to the second call. This contact is now online, while call A is on hold. The general status is online.

T7:     Call B is terminated and goes in wrap up. This has no effect on call A, which is still on hold. The general status is online.

T8:     The agent retrieves call A while call B is still in wrap up. Call A is online again. The general agent status is online.

T9:     When call A is terminated, it goes into wrap-up. Because there is no other active contact, the general status also goes into wrap-up.

This example demonstrates the handling of two active contacts at the same time.

 Example 3: two voice contacts and one email contact.

This illustration is the same as example 2 except that in this example the agent handles an email on top of the two calls.

 

This illustration shows three contacts (top arrows) with the appropriate agent actions, against the global agent statuses (middle arrow), during a fictive time period (bottom arrow).

T1:     Agent logs into the system and is set automatically into pause (this can vary depending on agent settings). When the agent clicks on ready, the agent status will change into waiting.

T2:     The agent is in waiting status.  This means that the agent waits to be connected to a contact.

T3:     When a contact is initiated (Call A in this example) to be connected to an agent, it receives the action ‘agent dialling’. This action describes the sequence during which a contact is trying to connect to an agent. In the meantime the general status of the agent is still ‘waiting’.

T4:     When the contact is connected to the agent, the ‘agent dialling’ sequence (agent action) ends and the ‘online’ sequence begins. This means that that the agent is connected to the contact and is talking to the contact. Since there is no other contact, the agent status is the same as the agent action, meaning ‘online’.

T5:     The agent initiates or receives a mail contact. This means that the agent is creating or responding to an email. The agent can do this while being online (talking to customer) with call A. Call ‘A’ as well as Mail ‘A’ are both online so the agent status is also online.

T6:     A third contact is initiated (Call B). This has no influence on the current call or on the email. The general status is online.

T7:     Call A is put on hold by the agent and call B is being connected to the agent. The agent responds to the second call. This contact is now online while call A is on hold and Mail A is online. The general status is online.

T8:     Call B is terminated and goes into wrap up. This has no effect on call A, which is still on hold and Mail A which is online. The general status is online.

T9:     The agent retrieves call A while call B is still in wrap-up. Call A is online again. Mail B is also still online. The general agent status is online.

T10:   In the meantime, the agent (still being online with Call A) has terminated the necessary actions on the mail. Call A is now the only active online contact. The general status is online.

T11:   When call A is terminated, it goes into wrap-up. Because there is no other active contact, the general status also goes into wrap-up.

This example demonstrates that the agent can handle multiple (in this case 2) online contacts at the same time.

General rules when dealing with multiple contacts.

The way the general agent statuses are derived from the individual agent contact actions is based on these rules:

-      When at least one of the active contacts is online, the general agent status will also be online.

-      When no contacts are online and at least one contact is in wrap-up, the general status will be wrap-up.

-      When no contacts are online or in wrap-up and the agent is not in pause, then the general status will be waiting.

Conclusion

The following concepts should be clearly understood:

-      An agent can have multiple (online) contacts at the same time.

-      The agent status indicates the global situation of an agent at a certain time.

-      The agent statuses are derived from the (different) agent actions.

-      The agent actions specify a certain condition of the contact during the whole online contact process.

-      When an agent has more than one active contact at the same time, the way the agent status is determined, is based on hierarchical rules between the actions.

Nixxis JavaScript

jsName

Overview

An array of 3 values to define a column.

Syntax

[int view, int category, int columnId]

Parameters

view
The id of the view.

category
The category id.

columnId
The column id.

Remark

To ease the use of column referencing, there are a set of functions to help, which use names instead of numbers. These functions have the following layout:

ViewName.CategoryName.ColumnName();

For example, to get the first name of an agent, it will be ‘Agent.Parameter.Firstname()’.

For a list of these functions, see chapter ‘description of the columns’ on page 26, look there in the different views.
